ObservatoryID.definition: The identifier of an Observatory resource.

ObservatoryRegion.definition: A spatial location distinguished by certain natural features or physical characteristics where an observatory is located.

ObservedBy.definition: Detected or originating from another resource.

ObservedRegion.definition: The portion of space measured by the instrument at the time of an observation. A region is distinguished by certain natural features or physical characteristics. It is the location of the observatory for in situ data, the location or region sensed by remote sensing observatories and the location-of-relevance for parameters that are derived from observational data.

Offline.definition: Not directly accessible electronically. This includes resources which may to be moved to an on-line status in response to a given request.

OperatingSpan.definition: The interval in time from the first point at which an instrument or spacecraft was producing and sending data until the last such time, ignoring possible gaps.

OperatingSystem.definition: The software that supports a computer's basic functions, such as scheduling tasks, executing applications, and controlling peripherals.

Optical.definition: Photons with a wavelength range: 380 to 760 nm

ORCIdentifier.definition: A Open Researcher Contributor (ORC) identifier which is a unique alphanumeric string assigned by a registration agency (https://orcid.org/) to identify an individual. It has the format xxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx

OrganizationName.definition: A unit within a company or other entity (e.g., Government agency or branch of service) within which many projects are managed as a whole.

Orientation.definition: The specification of the directional alignment of an object or measurement in a reference coordinate system. The orientation such as a spacecraft spin axis attitude is usually expressed as one or more angles relative to the basis axes of some specified physical space usually together with the date/time of the observation.

Other.definition: Not classified with more specific terms. The context of its usage may be described in related text.

Outer.definition: The region of the heliosphere extending radially outward from just outside 1 AU to the heliospheric termination shock.

OutputProperty.definition: A container of attributes regarding an output property of an application.

Overview.definition: A web page that provides and overview of available data and links.

Parallel.definition: Having the same direction as a given direction

Parameter.definition: A container of information regarding a parameter whose values are part of the product. Every product contains or can be related to one or more parameters.

ParameterKey.definition: The name or identifier which can be used to access the parameter in the resource. The associated value is dependent on the service used to access the resource. For columnar ASCII data, use "Column_X" for a single-element parameter and "Column_X-Column_Y" for a multi-element parameter, where X and Y are the relevant column index. The first column index is 1.

ParentID.definition: The resource identifier for a resource that a resource is a part of. The resource inherits the attributes of the referenced resource. Attributes defined in the resource override attributes of the parent in the manner prescribed by the containing resource.

PartiallyRestricted.definition: Some portions of the resource have restricted access, the rest is open access. Typically this is for accumulating data collections where some data is under review before being publicly released.

Particle.definition: A description of the types of particles observed in the measurement. This includes both direct observations and inferred observations.

ParticleCorrelator.definition: An instrument which correlates particle flux to help identify wave/particle interactions.

ParticleDetector.definition: An instrument which detects particle flux!!!

ParticleQuantity.definition: A characterization of the physical properties of the particle.

ParticleRadius.definition: The mean radius for a Gaussian distribution of particles with an axial ratio of 2 and a distribution width that varies as 0.5 radius. A value of zero means no cloud was detected.

ParticleRigidity.definition: The particle momentum per unit charge. The particle Rigidity, R, is equal to pc/Ze.

ParticleType.definition: A characterization of the kind of particle observed by the measurement.

PartOf.definition: A portion of a larger resource.

Passive.definition: Movement or effect produced by outside influence. A passive measurement is one which does not produce a transmission or excitation as a part of the measurement cycle.

PDF.definition: A document expressed in the Portable Document Format (PDF) as defined by Adobe.

PDS3.definition: The. Planetary Data System, version 3 (PDS3) standard provides guidelines on how a data producer should construct a data set suitable for long-term archiving. The standard contains a number of requirements in terms of dataset structure and documentation that should allow for any PDS compliant data set to be used and understood in the long term. Each PDS3 data product must be labelled in ASCII with full details on the structure and content of the product. The label can be attached to the data file itself or detached in a separate 'label' file with the suffix LBL. The PDS3 standard is described at: https://pds.jpl.nasa.gov/datastandards/pds3/standards/ Since 2011, PDS3 has superseded by the PDS4 archiving standard. However, many data files still exist that are stored by using the PDS3 standard.

PDS4.definition: The Planetary Data System, version 4 (PDS4) standard provides guidelines on how a data producer should construct a data set suitable for long-term archiving. The standard contains a number of requirements in terms of dataset structure and documentation that should allow for any PDS compliant data set to be used and understood in the long term. Each PDS4 bundle consists of two files, one containing the data and the other an eXtensible Markup Language (XML) file containing the label. PDS4 recognises four base data structures, array, table, parsable byte stream and encoded byte stream with arrays and tables most commonly in use. The PDS4 standard is described at: https://pds.jpl.nasa.gov/datastandards/documents/current-version.shtml. The PDS4 archiving standard has been required for data archives from NASA-funded planetary missions and for small data archives since 2011.

Peak.definition: The maximum value for the quantity in question, over a period of time which is usually equal to the cadence.

Per.definition: The time interval over which a characterization applies. For example, the number of bytes generated each day.

Perpendicular.definition: At right angles to a given direction.

PersonID.definition: The identifier assigned to a Person description.

PersonName.definition: The words used to address an individual.

Perturbation.definition: Variations in the state of a system.

Phase.definition: A point or portion in a recurring series of changes.

PhaseAngle.definition: Phase difference between two or more waves, normally expressed in degrees.

PhaseSpaceDensity.definition: The number of particles per unit volume in the six-dimensional space of position and velocity.

PhenomenonType.definition: The characteristics or categorization of an event type.

Phobos.definition: The larger and inner most moon of Mars.

PhoneNumber.definition: The symbols and numerals required to contact an individual by telephone. The string may contain punctuation marks such as dash (-) or dot (.) to separate fields within the string.

Photograph.definition: An image (positive or negative) registered on a piece of photo-sensitive paper

PhotographicPlate.definition: A rigid (typically glass) medium that functions like film. Its rigidity is for guarding against image distortion due to medium deformation (caused by heat and humidity). Photographic plates are often used for astronomical photography.

Photometer.definition: An instrument which measures the strength of electromagnetic radiation within a spectral band which can range from ultraviolet to infrared and includes the visible spectrum.

PhotomultiplierTube.definition: A vacuum phototube that is an extremely sensitive detector of light in the ultraviolet, visible, and near-infrared ranges of the electromagnetic spectrum.

Photon.definition: Electromagnetic waves detected by techniques that utilize their corpuscular character (e.g., CCD, CMOS, photomultipliers).

Photopolarimeter.definition: An instrument which measures the intensity and polarization or radiant energy. A photopolarimeter is a combination of a photometer and a polarimeter.

Photosphere.definition: The atmospheric layer of the Sun or a star from which continuum radiation, especially optical, is emitted to space. For the Sun, the photosphere is about 500 km thick.

PitchAngleRange.definition: The range of possible pitch angles for a group of particle observations.

PlasmaBeta.definition: The ratio of the plasma pressure (nkT) to the magnetic pressure (B^2/2mu0) of the SUM(nkT)/(B^2/2mu0).

PlasmaFrequency.definition: A number-density-dependent characteristic frequency of a plasma.

Plasmagram.definition: The characterization of signal strengths in active sounding measurements as a function of virtual range or signal delay time and sounding frequency. A Plasmagram is also referred to as an Ionogram.

Plasmasphere.definition: A region of the magnetosphere consisting of low energy (cool) plasma. It is located above the ionosphere. The outer boundary of the plasmasphere is known as the plasmapause, which is defined by an order of magnitude drop in plasma density.

PlasmaWaves.definition: Self-consistent collective oscillations of particles and fields (electric and magnetic) in a plasma.

Platform.definition: A collection of components which can be positioned and oriented as a single unit. A platform may contain other platforms. For example, a spacecraft is a platform which may have components that can be articulated and are also considered platforms.

Pluto.definition: The ninth (sub)planet from the sun in our solar system.

PNG.definition: A digital format for still images. Portable Network Graphics (PNG)

Polar.definition: The region near the pole of a body. For a magnetosphere the polar region is the area where magnetic field lines are open and includes the auroral zone.

PolarAngle.definition: The angle between the position or measured vector and the k-axis of the coordinate system. Mathematically defined as arctan([SQRT(i^2+j^2)]/k). This term could be also applied to angles between the vector and other components, for example the IMF cone angle defined as arccos(Bx/Bt).

PolarAngleRange.definition: The range of possible polar angles for a group of energy observations. Defaults units are degrees.

PolarCap.definition: The areas of the globe surrounding the poles and consisting of the region north of 60 degrees north latitude an the region south of 60 degrees south latitude.

Policy.definition: A deliberate system of principles to guide decisions and achieve rational outcomes. A policy is a statement of intent, and is implemented as a procedure or protocol.

Polarization.definition: Direction of the electric vector of an electromagnetic wave. The wave can be linearly polarized in any direction perpendicular to the direction of travel, circularly polarized (clockwise or counterclockwise), unpolarized, or mixtures of the above.

Positional.definition: The specification of the location of an object or measurement within a reference coordinate system. The position is usually expressed as a set of values corresponding to the location along a set of orthogonal axes together with the date/time of the observation.

Positron.definition: An elementary particle consisting of a charge of positive electricity equal to about 1.602 x 10^(-19) Coulomb and having a mass when at rest of about 9.109534 x 10^(-28) gram.

Poster.definition: A set of information arranged on a single page or sheet, typically in a large format.

Postscript.definition: A page description programming language created by Adobe Systems Inc. that is a device-independent industry standard for representing text and graphics.

Potential.definition: The work required per unit charge to move a charge from a reference point to a point at infinity (electric potential is defined to be zero). The electric potential of a spacecraft is often referred to as the "spacecraft potential". The spacecraft potential is the electric potential of the spacecraft relative to the potential of the nearby plasma. The spacecraft potential is non-zero because the spacecraft charges to the level that the emitted photoelectron flux going to infinity is balanced by the plasma electron flux to the spacecraft.

PowerSpectralDensity.definition: The Power Spectral Density, PSD, is the measure of signal power content versus frequency, energy, wave number, etc. A PSD is typically used to characterize broadband random signals. The amplitude of the PSD is normalized by the spectral resolution employed to digitize the signal.

PoyntingFlux.definition: Electromagnetic energy flux transported by a wave characterized as the rate of energy transport per unit area per steradian.

Presentation.definition: A set of information that is used when communicating to an audience.

Pressure.definition: The force per unit area exerted by a particle distribution or field.

PrincipalInvestigator.definition: An individual who is the administrative and scientific lead for an investigation.

Print.definition: A sheet of any written or printed material which may include notes or graphics. Multiple printed pages may be bound into a manuscript or book.

Prerequisites.definition: A thing that is required to be installed on your computer in order to run or compile the software.

ExecutionEnvironment.definition: An execution platform for software which includes an operating system and necessary hardware.

PriorID.definition: The resource identifier for a resource that is superseded or replaced by a resource.

Probable.definition: Likely given the available evidence. Considered in the range of 4-7 on a scale of 0-10.

ProcessingLevel.definition: The standard classification of the processing performed on the product.

ProductKey.definition: A string of characters used to uniquely identify a particular product within a Repository. The style or format of the identifier is determined by the Repository. The kinds of resources which can be acessed include, but are not limited to, numerical data, display data, documents and event lists. The method to access the product is determined by the attributes of an access service.

Profile.definition: Measurements of a quantity as a function of height above an object such as the limb of a body.

ProgramManager.definition: An individual whose major task entails direction of program team members such that the full organization achieves the objectives and goals of a program. The Program Manager is expected to provide clear guidance and resolve conflicts and issues while maintaining focus on achieving program success.

ProgramScientist.definition: A program scientist is someone who performs a range of scientific program planning duties, takes responsibility for the science content of flight mission programs or projects. A program scientist develops, reviews, and provides recommendations for proposed program requirements, expected results, budgetary estimates and also establishes methods and procedures to reduce program costs, provides expert advice to management on strategic planning and program development, develops and manages research program, and presents issues and proposes solutions to senior management.

Project.definition: The name of an organized activity with a stated goal or objective.

ProjectEngineer.definition: An engineer tasked with the full suite of responsibilities as a project transitions through requirements derivation and preliminary design into controlled hardware development, assembly and environmental testing. The Project Engineer manages a team while developing the cadence of hardware manufacturing and assembly until instrument deployment and through the end of the mission.

Projection.definition: A measure of the length of a position or measured vector as projected into a plane of the coordinate system.

ProjectManager.definition: An individual whose major task entails direction of project team members such that the full organization achieves the objectives and goals of the mission. The Project Manager is expected to provide clear guidance and resolve conflicts and issues while maintaining focus on achieving mission success.

ProjectScientist.definition: An individual who is an expert in the phenomenon and related physics explored by the project. A project scientist may also have a managerial role within the project.

PropagationTime.definition: Time difference between transmission and reception of a wave in an active wave experiment.

Property.definition: A container of attributes regarding the property of an application.

ProportionalCounter.definition: An instrument which measures energy of ionization radiation based on interactions with a gas.

Proteus.definition: The second largest moon of Neptune.

Proton.definition: An elementary particle that is a constituent of all atomic nuclei, that carries a positive charge numerically equal to the charge of an electron, and that has a mass of 1.673 x 10^(-24) gram.

ProviderName.definition: The source, or original provider, of the data (for example, PDS PPI).

ProviderProcessingLevel.definition: The provider specific information on the processing performed on the product. This should include the provider processing level designation and information about the intended use of the product. For example, if it is to be used for machine learning or other high level applications.

ProviderResourceName.definition: A short textual description of a resource used by the provider which may be used to identify a resource.

ProviderVersion.definition: Describes the release or edition of the product used by the provider. The formation rule may vary between providers. It is intended to aid in queries to the provider regarding the product.

Pseudo.definition: Similar to or having the appearance of something else. Can be used to indicate an estimation or approximation of a particular quantity.

PublicationDate.definition: The date that the work (document, data, images or other types of resources) was first issued.

PublicationInfo.definition: Additional information, not located elsewhere in the resource description, that is related to the issuing of a work (document, data, images or other types of resources) and is also required to mint a DOI.

PublishedBy.definition: The name or the company, organization or individual that issues the work (document, data, images or other types of resources).

Publisher.definition: An individual, organization, institution or government department responsible for the production and dissemination of a document.

Puck.definition: The largest inner spherical moon of Uranus.

QuadrisphericalAnalyser.definition: An instrument used for the 3-D detection of plasma, energetic electrons and ions, and for positive-ion composition measurements.

Qualifier.definition: Characterizes the refinement to apply to a type or attribute of a quantity.

Quantity.definition: A value that describes a characteristic of a system.

QuickTime.definition: A format for digital movies, as defined by Apple Computer. See <http://developer.apple.com/quicktime/>

Radar.definition: An instrument that uses directional properties of returned power to infer spatial and/or other characteristics of a remote object.

Radiance.definition: A radiometric measurement that describes the amount of electromagnetic radiation that passes through or is emitted from a particular area, and falls within a given solid angle in a specified direction. They are used to characterize both emission from diffuse sources and reflection from diffuse surfaces.

RadiationBelt.definition: The region within a magnetosphere where high-energy particles could potentially be trapped in a magnetic field.

RadioBurst.definition: Emissions of the sun in radio wavelengths from centimeters to dekameters, under both quiet and disturbed conditions. Radio Bursts can be "Type I" consisting of many short, narrow-band bursts in the metric range (300 - 50 MHz).; "Type II" consisting of narrow-band emission that begins in the meter range (300 MHz) and sweeps slowly (tens of minutes) toward dekameter wavelengths (10 MHz).; "Type III" consisting of narrow-band bursts that sweep rapidly (seconds) from decimeter to dekameter wavelengths (500 - 0.5 MHz); and "Type IV" consisting of a smooth continuum of broad-band bursts primarily in the meter range (300 - 30 MHz).

RadioFrequency.definition: Photons with a wavelength range: 100,000 to 1.00x10^11 nm.

Radiometer.definition: An instrument for detecting or measuring radiant energy. Radiometers are commonly limited to infrared radiation.

Ratio.definition: The relative magnitudes of two quantities.

Raw.definition: Data in its original state with no processing to account for calibration. Similar to NASA Level 0.

RealPart.definition: Any number z can in general be represented by its complex form with z = a + ib where i, which is defined as the square root of -1, signifies the imaginary component of the number z. The coefficient a is called the real part of the complex number z.

Registry.definition: A location or facility where resources are cataloged.

RelativeStopDate.definition: An indication of the nominal end date relative to the present.

ReleaseDate.definition: The date and time when a resource is made available. The availability of a resource coincides with the release of a resource description. If the Release Date is specified as a future date then it indicates that resource should not be made available until that time. However, this is only advisory and in practice the Release Date should be the actual date the resource description was published.

Remote1AU.definition: A roughly toroidal region that includes the Earth's orbit, but exclusive of the region near the Earth.

RenderingAxis.definition: A reference component of a plot or rendering of data. A plot typically is a 2-dimensional rendering with a horizontal and verticle axis. A third dimension can be introduced with a color coding of the rendered data.

RenderingHints.definition: Attributes to aid in the rendering of parameter.

Report.definition: A document which describes the findings of some individual or group.

Repository.definition: A location or facility where resources are stored.

RepositoryID.definition: The identifier of an Repository resource.

ResonanceSounder.definition: A combination of a radio receiver and a pulsed transmitter used to study the plasma surrounding a spacecraft by identifying resonances or cut-offs (of the wave dispersion relation), whose frequencies are related to the ambient plasma density and magnetic field. When the transmitter is off it is essentially a high frequency-resolution spectral power receiver.

ResourceHeader.definition: Attributes of a resource which pertain to the provider of the resource and descriptive information about the resource.

ResourceID.definition: A Resource ID is a URI that has the form "scheme://authority/path" where "scheme" is "spase" for those resources administered through the SPASE framework, "authority" is the unique identifier for the resource provider registered within the SPASE framework and "path" is the unique identifier of the resource within the context of the "authority". The resource ID must be unique within the SPASE framework.

ResourceName.definition: A short textual description of a resource which may be useful when read by a person.

Restricted.definition: Access to the product is regulated and requires some form of identification.

RetardingPotentialAnalyser.definition: An instrument which measures ion temperatures and ion concentrations using a planar ion trap.

RevisionEvent.definition: A specific change that improves or upgrades.

RevisionHistory.definition: A history of changes that improve or upgrade.

RevisionOf.definition: A modified version of a resource instance.

Rhea.definition: The second-largest moon of Saturn and the ninth-largest moon in the Solar System.

RingCurrent.definition: One of the major current systems confined within planetary magnetospheres. The ring current circles in the magnetic equatorial plane of magnetospheres. It is generated by the longitudinal drift of energetic charged particles trapped on inner, dipole-like magnetospheric field lines. At the Earth, the ring current is carried by 10 to 200 keV charged particles typically located at L-shells between 3 and 6. The ring current is also the primary driver of the Sym H and Dst Indices of magnetic storm activity at the Earth.

RINEX2.definition: Receiver Independent Exchange Format (RINEX) - version 2.*, is a data interchange format for raw satellite navigation system data. https://files.igs.org/pub/data/format/rinex211.txt

RINEX3.definition: Receiver Independent Exchange Format (RINEX) - version 3.*, is a data interchange format for raw satellite navigation system data. https://files.igs.org/pub/data/format/rinex300.pdf

Riometer.definition: An instrument which measure the signal strength in various directions of the galactic radio signals. Variations in these signals are influenced by solar flare activity and geomagnetic storm and substorm processes.

Role.definition: The assigned or assumed function or position of an individual.

RORIdentifier.definition: The assigned Research Organization Registry (ROR) identifier. See https://ror.org/

RotationMatrix.definition: A tensor that is used to perform vector data transformation from one coordinate system to another.

RTN.definition: Radial Tangential Normal. Typically centered at a spacecraft. Used for IMF and plasma V vectors. The X axis (radial) is set as the primary axis, and is defined as the axis pointing from the spacecraft to the Sun. The Z axis (tangential) is set as the secondary axis, and is defined as that portion of the solar North rotational axis which is perpendicular to the primary axis. The Y axis (normal) is defined as Z cross X.

S3_BUCKET.definition: A container of objects that comply with the Amazon Simple Storage Service (S3) specifications. A bucket has a unique, user-assigned key (name). A bucket can contain any number of objects with an aggregate size of 5 gigabytes. A bucket may be accompanied by up to 2 kilobytes of metadata.

Saturn.definition: The sixth planet from the sun in our solar system.

SC.definition: Spacecraft - A coordinate system defined by the spacecraft geometry and/or spin. Often has Z axis parallel to spacecraft spin vector. X and Y axes may or may not corotate with the spacecraft. See SR and SR2 below.

Scalar.definition: A quantity that is completely specified by its magnitude and has no direction.

ScaleMax.definition: The maximum value that the variable is expected to attain. Used, for example, by automated plotting software.

ScaleMin.definition: The minimum value that the variable is expected to attain. Used, for example, by automated plotting software.

ScaleType.definition: The scaling to apply to an axis. If this attribute is not present, linear scale should be assumed.

Scientist.definition: An individual who is an expert in the phenomenon and related physics represented by the resource.

ScintillationDetector.definition: An instrument which detects flouresences of a material which is excited by high energy (ionizing) electromagnetic or charged particle radiation.

SE.definition: Solar Ecliptic - A heliocentric coordinate system where the Z axis is normal to the ecliptic plane, positive northward. X axis is positive towards the first point of Aries (from Earth to Sun at vernal equinox). Same as HAE above. See <http://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/space/helios/coor_des.html>

Search.definition: A web search interface that requires additional input.

SearchCoil.definition: An instrument which measures the time variation of the magnetic flux threading a loop by measurement of the electric potential difference induced between the ends of the wire.

SectorBoundaryCrossing.definition: A sector boundary crossing is a transit by a spacecraft across the heliospheric current sheet separating the dominantly outward (away-from-the-sun) interplanetary magnetic field of one hemisphere of the heliosphere from the dominantly inward (toward-the-sun) polarity of the other hemisphere.  Such crossings have multi-day intervals of opposite IMF dominant polarities on either side.

Service.definition: A location or facility that can perform a well defined task.

Set.definition: A collection of items for a particular purpose.

SHA1.definition: Secure Hash Algorithm (SHA), a 160-bit message digest algorithm developed by the NSA and described in Federal Information Processing Standard (FIPS) publication 180-1.

SHA256.definition: Secure Hash Algorithm (SHA), a 256-bit message digest algorithm developed by the NSA and described in Federal Information Processing Standard (FIPS) publication 180-1.

Size.definition: The number of elements in each dimension of a multi-dimensional array. A scalar has a size of 1. A multi-dimensional vector will have a size for each dimension. Note that the number of elements in the size of an N-dimensional array conveys the array's dimensionality while the product of those numbers conveys the total number of elements in the array. When size is used to describe a tensor it is the number of elements in the tensor. As such it has a limited set of values. A tensor of rank 1 has a size of 3, rank 2 a size of 9, rank 3 a size of 27 and rank n a size of 3^n.

SM.definition: Solar Magnetic - A geocentric coordinate system where the Z axis is northward along Earth's dipole axis, X axis is in plane of z axis and Earth-Sun line, positive sunward. See Russell, 1971.

Software.definition: An application which can be installed, built or readily used.

SoftwareVersion.definition: Describes the edition of the software release. The formation rule for the version may vary between software packages. It is intended to aid in queries to the software provider regarding the software.

SoftXRays.definition: X-Rays with an energy range of 0.12 keV to 12 keV.

SolarFlare.definition: An explosive event in the Sun's atmosphere which produces electromagnetic radiation across the electromagnetic spectrum at multiple wavelengths from long-wave radio to the shortest wavelength gamma rays.

SolarUVFlux.definition: The amount of Ultraviolet energy originating from the Sun passing through a unit area in a unit time.

SolarWindExtreme.definition: Intervals of unusually large or small values of solar wind attributes such as flow speed and ion density.

SolidAngle.definition: Integration over the angle in three-dimensional space that an object subtends at a point.

SolidStateDetector.definition: A detector of the charge carriers (electrons and holes) generated in semiconductors by energy deposited by gamma ray photons. Also known as a "semiconductor detector".

SonicMachNumber.definition: The ratio of the bulk flow speed to the speed of sound in the medium.

Sounder.definition: An instrument which measures the radiances from an object. A sounder may measure radiances at multiple spectral ranges.

SoundSpeed.definition: The speed at which sound travels through a medium.

Source.definition: The location and attributes of an object.

SourceType.definition: A characterization of the function or purpose of the source.

SouthAtlanticAnomalyRegion.definition: The region where the Earth's inner van Allen radiation belt makes its closest approach to the planet's surface. The result is that, for a given altitude, the radiation intensity is higher over this region than elsewhere.

SpacecraftOrbitPlane.definition: A coordinate system where X lies in the plane normal to and in the direction of motion of the spacecraft, Z is normal to this plane and Y completes the triad in a right-handed coordinate system.

SpacecraftPotentialControl.definition: An instrument to control the electric potential of a spacecraft with respect to the ambient plasma by emitting a variable current of positive ions.

Spase.definition: Space Physics Archive Search and Extract (SPASE). The outermost container or envelope for SPASE metadata. This indicates the start of the SPASE metadata.

SpatialCoverage.definition: A region of space defined by the latitude, longitude and altitude in a geographic coordinate system.

NorthernmostLatitude.definition: The latitude furthest to the north in a geographic coordinate system.

SouthernmostLatitude.definition: The latitude furthest to the south in a geographic coordinate system.

EasternmostLongitude.definition: The longitude furthest to the east in a geographic coordinate system.

WesternmostLongitude.definition: The longitude furthest to the west in a geographic coordinate system.

CenterLatitude.definition: The latitude in the center of a region in a geographic coordinate system.

CenterLongitude.definition: The longitude in the center of a region in a geographic coordinate system.

CenterElevation.definition: The elevation in the center of a region above a surface (such as sea level or land) of a planet or natural satellite.

MinimumElevation.definition: The lowest vertical elevation of region above a surface (such as sea level or land) of a planet or natural satellite.

MaximumElevation.definition: The highest vertical elevation of region above a surface (such as sea level or land) of a planet or natural satellite.

Specification.definition: A detailed description of the requirements and other aspects of an object or component that may be used to develop an implementation.

Spectral.definition: Characterized as a range or continuum of frequencies.

SpectralPowerReceiver.definition: A radio receiver which determines the power spectral density of the electric or magnetic field, or both, at one or more frequencies.

SpectralRange.definition: The general term used to describe wavelengths or frequencies within a given span of values for those quantities.

Spectrogram.definition: The characterization of signal strengths as a function of frequency (or energy) and time.

Spectrometer.definition: An instrument that measures the component wavelengths of light (or other electromagnetic radiation) by splitting the light up into its component wavelengths.

Spectrum.definition: The distribution of a characteristic of a physical system or phenomenon, such as the energy emitted by a radiant source, arranged in the order of wavelengths.

Spherical.definition: A coordinate representation of a position vector or of a measured vector by its magnitude and two direction angles. The angles are relative to the base axes of the coordinate system used. Typically the angles are phi [azimuth angle, =arctan (j/i)] and theta, where theta may be a polar angle, arctan {[SQRT(i^2+j^2)]/k}, or an elevation angle, arctan [k/SQRT (i^2+j^2)].

SPICE.definition: SPICE is an ancillary information system that provides scientists and engineers the capability to include space geometry and event data into mission design, science observation planning, and science data analysis software. The staff of the NASA Navigation and Ancillary Information Facility, NAIF, which is located at JPL provides SPICE support for planetary, heliophysics, and Earth science missions, see https://naif.jpl.nasa.gov/naif/index.html. This SPICE has been adapted from text on NAF hosted web pages.

SpinPeriod.definition: The time required for an object such as a spacecraft or planet to perform one full rotation in a given frame of reference.

SpinPhase.definition: An angular based or normalized parameter that specifies the spin state of an object such as a spacecraft or planet in a specific coordinate system usually together with the date/time of the observation.

SpinRate.definition: The angular rate of change of the spin angle of an object such as a spacecraft or planet.

SR.definition: Spin Reference - A special case of a Spacecraft (SC) coordinate system for a spinning spacecraft. Z is parallel to the spacecraft spin vector. X and Y rotate with the spacecraft. See <http://cdpp.cnes.fr/00428.pdf>

SR2.definition: Spin Reference 2 - A special case of a Spacecraft (SC) coordinate system for a spinning spacecraft. Z is parallel to the spacecraft spin vector. X is in the plane defined by Z and the spacecraft-Sun line, positive sunward. See <http://cdpp.cnes.fr/00428.pdf>

SSE.definition: Spacecraft Solar Ecliptic - A coordinate system used for deep space spacecraft, for example Helios. - X axis from spacecraft to Sun. Z axis normal to ecliptic plane, positive northward. Note: Angle between normals to ecliptic and to Helios orbit plane ~ 0.25 deg.

SSE_L.definition: Selenocentric Solar Ecliptic.  The X axis points from the center of the Earth's moon to the sun, the Z axis is normal to the ecliptic plane, positive northward.  And the Y axis completes the right-handed set of axes.

StackPlot.definition: A representation of data showing multiple sets of observations on a single plot, possibly offsetting each plot by some uniform amount.

StandardDeviation.definition: The square root of the average of the squares of deviations about the mean of a set of data. Standard deviation is a statistical measure of spread or variability.

StartDate.definition: The specification of a starting point in time.

StokesParameters.definition: A set of four parameters (usually called I,Q, U and V) which describe the polarization state of an electromagnetic wave propagating through space.

StopDate.definition: The specification of a stopping point in time.

Storage.definition: The component of your computer that allows you to store and access data on a long-term basis. Indicate units with standard byte scales such as KB, MB, GB, TB and PB.

Strahl.definition: A distribution of particles concentrated in a narrow energy band. The band may be may be aligned with a secondary feature. For example, it may occur in a narrow cone aligned with the mean magnetic field direction.

Stratosphere.definition: The layer of the atmosphere that extends from the troposphere to about 30 km, temperature increases with height. The stratosphere contains the ozone layer.

StreamInteractionRegion.definition: The region (SIR) where two solar wind streams, typically having differing characteristics and solar sources, abut up against (and possibly partially interpenetrate) each other.

Strong.definition: Highly likely given the available evidence. Considered in the range of 7-10 on a scale of 0-10.

Structure.definition: The organization and relationship of individual values within a quantity.

Style.definition: The manner in which a response from a URL is presented.

SubAuroralRegion.definition: When considering the case of the Earth, the sub-auroral region typically refers to two latitudinal bands, one in the northern hemisphere and the other in the southern hemisphere extending from about 50 degrees to low 60 degrees. The concept sub-auroral regions does not apply to all bodies in the solar system and different latitudinal ranges would apply for each body case by case. The sub-auroral regions may be defined by using either planetographic or magnetic coordinates if the magnetic dipole is closely aligned with the spin axis of a magnetized body. Ground magnetometers located at sub-auroral latitudes on the Earth measure a mixture of activity driven by auroral zone currents and the ring current.

Substorm.definition: A process by which plasma in the magnetotail becomes energized at a fast rate.

Sun.definition: The star upon which our solar system is centered.

Superhalo.definition: The part of an object or distribution surrounding some central body or distribution evident in a second break in the distribution function (e.g., a different power law).  It consists of a population at a higher energies than for a halo.

Support.definition: Information useful in understanding the context of an observation, typically observed or measured coincidentally with a physical observation.

SupportQuantity.definition: A characterization of the support information.

Surface.definition: The outermost area of a solid object.

Symmetric.definition: Equal distribution about one or more axes.

TAP.definition: The table access protocol (TAP) defines a service protocol for accessing general table data, including astronomical catalogs as well as general database tables. Access is provided for both database and table metadata as well as for actual table data. https://wiki.ivoa.net/twiki/bin/view/IVOA/TableAccess

TAR.definition: A file format used to collate collections of files into one larger file, for distribution or archiving, while preserving file system information such as user and group permissions, dates, and directory structures. The format was standardized by POSIX.1-1988 and later POSIX.1-2001.

TeamLeader.definition: An individual who is the designated leader of an investigation.

TeamMember.definition: An individual who is a major participant in an investigation.

TechnicalContact.definition: An individual who can provide specific information with regard to the resource or supporting software.

TechnicalNote.definition: A document summarizing the performance and other technical characteristics of a product, machine, component, subsystem or software in sufficient detail to be used by an engineer or researcher.

Telemetry.definition: Parameters that include full packets of data from monitoring devices or the memory addresses of datum within telemetry packets. The data comprising telemetry packets are typically expressed by using non-physical engineering units and may be used to express a variety of device operating conditions such as command acceptance/execution, housekeeping, event characterization, memory dumps, and science data. Telemetry packets may be raw or unpacked.

Temperature.definition: A measure of the kinetic energy of random motion with respect to the average. Temperature is properly defined only for an equilibrium particle distribution (Maxwellian distribution).

Template.definition: A URI template that contains special fields as defined in URI Template specification <http://tsds.org/uri_templates>.

TemporalDescription.definition: A characterization of the time over which the measurement was taken.

Tensor.definition: A generalized linear "quantity" or "geometrical entity" that can be expressed as a multi-dimensional array relative to a choice of basis of the particular space on which it is defined.

Tethys.definition: The third largest moon of Saturn.

Text.definition: A sequence of characters which may have an imposed structure or organization.

TFCat.definition: Time-Frequency Catalogue (TFCat) is a catalogue model & transfer format for spectro-temporal features. https://gitlab.obspm.fr/maser/catalogues/catalogue-format

ThermalPlasma.definition: Measurements of the plasma in the energy regime where the most of the plasma occurs. May be the basic fluxes in the form of distribution functions or the derived bulk parameters (density, flow velocity, etc.).

ThermalSpeed.definition: For a Maxwellian distribution, the difference between the mean speed and the speed within which ~69% (one sigma) of all the members of the speed distribution occur.

Thermosphere.definition: The layer of the atmosphere that extends from the Mesosphere to 640+ km, temperature increasing with height.

Thumbnail.definition: A small representation of an image which is suitable to infer what the full-sized imaged is like.

TIFF.definition: A binary format for still pictures. Tagged Image Format File (TIFF). Originally developed by Aldus and now controlled by Adobe.

TIIS.definition: Kronian Solar Orbital - A coordinate system related to Saturn where X is anti-sunward, Y along the orbital velocity direction.

TimeOfFlight.definition: An instrument which measures the time it takes for a particle to travel between two detectors.

TimeSeries.definition: A representation of data showing a set of observations taken at different points in time and charted as a time series.

TimeSpan.definition: The duration of an interval in time.

Titan.definition: The largest moon of Saturn and the second-largest moon in the Solar System.

Titania.definition: The largest moon of Uranus and the eighth largest moon in the Solar System.

Topside.definition: The region at the upper most areas of the ionosphere.

Total.definition: The summation of quantities over all possible species.

TotalPressure.definition: In an MHD fluid it is the number density (N) times Boltzmann constant times the temperature in Kelvin.

Trace.definition: The sum of the elements on the main diagonal (the diagonal from the upper left to the lower right) of a square matrix.

TransitionRegion.definition: A very narrow (<100 km) layer between the chromosphere and the corona where the temperature rises abruptly from about 8000 to about 500,000 K.

Troposphere.definition: The lowest layer of the atmosphere which begins at the surface and extends to between 7 km (4.4 mi) at the poles and 17 km (10.6 mi) at the equator, with some variation due to weather factors.

UCD.definition: The nature of a physical parameter expressed using the IVOA UCD1+ controlled vocabulary.

UDF.definition: Universal Data Format (UDF). The Optical Technology Storage Association's Universal Disk Format, based on ISO 13346. See <http://www.osta.org/specs/index.htm>

Ultraviolet.definition: Photons with a wavelength range: 10 to 400 nm.

Umbriel.definition: The third largest and fourth most massive moon of Uranus.

Uncalibrated.definition: Duplicate data are removed from the data stream and data are time ordered. Values are not adjusted for any potential biases or external factors. Similar to NASA Level 1.

Uncertainty.definition: A statistically defined discrepancy between a measured quantity and the true value of that quantity that cannot be corrected by calculation or calibration.

Units.definition: A description of the standardized measurement increments in which a value is specified. The description is represented as a mathematical phrase. Units should be represented by widely accepted representation. For example, units should conform to the International System of Units (SI) which is maintained by BIPM (Bureau International des Poids et Mesures (see <http://www.bipm.fr/> ) when appropriate or use tokens like "Re" to represent units of the Radius of the Earth. Within a phrase the circumflex (^) is used to indicate a power, a star (*) is used to indicate multiplication and a slash (/) division. When symbols are not separated by a mathematical operator, multiplication is assumed. Symbols for base units can be found at: <http://www.bipm.fr/en/si/si_brochure/chapter2/2-1/#symbols> and those for common derived units can be found at: <http://www.bipm.fr/en/si/derived_units/2-2-2.html>

UnitsConversion.definition: The multiplicative factor for converting a unit into International System of Units (SI) units. The factor is expressed in the form "number > x", where "number" is a numerical value and "x" is the appropriate SI units. The basic SI units are Enumerated: m (meter), N (newton), kg (kilogram), Pa (pascal), s (second), Hz (hertz), A (ampere), V (volt), K (kelvin), W (watt), rad (radian), J (joule), sr (steradian), C (coulomb), T (tesla), ohm (ohm), mho (mho or seimens), H (henry), and F (farad). Two useful units which are not SI units are: degree (angle), and unitless (no units). An example is: "1.0E-9>T" which converts the units, presumable nT, to Tesla. Another example is: "1.0e+3>m/s" which converts a velocity expressed in kilometers per second to meters per second.

Unlikely.definition: Not likely given the available evidence. Considered in the range of 0 on a scale of 0-10.

Unspecified.definition: A value which is not provided.

UpperHybridFrequency.definition: Upper hybrid oscillations involve longitudinal motions of electrons perpendicular to the magnetic field. The upper hybrid frequency, Φ<sub>UH</sub>, is governed by the relationshipΦ<sub>UH</sub>^2 = Φ<sub>pe</sub>^2 + Θ<sub>ce</sub>^2 where Φ<sub>pe</sub> is electron plasma frequency and Θ<sub>ce</sub> is the electron cyclotron frequency.

Uranus.definition: The eighth planet from the sun in our solar system.

URL.definition: Uniform Resource Locator (URL) is the global address of documents and other resources on the World Wide Web. The first part of the address indicates what protocol to use, and the second part specifies the IP address or the domain name where the resource is located followed by the pathname of the resource. A URL is specified in the form protocol://server.domain.name:port/pathname. Example protocols are HTTP or FTP, server domain name is the Internet name.

User.definition: An individual who utilizes a resource or service.

ValueAdded.definition: Calibrated data that has been mapped on uniform space-time grid scales with gaps, flags and out-of-range values replaced with appropriate values. Similar to NASA Level 3.

ValueFormat.definition: A string defining the output format used when extracting data values out to a file or screen. The magnitude and the number of significant figures needed should be carefully considered. The output format string can be in either Fortran or C syntax.

Variance.definition: A measure of dispersion of a set of data points around their mean value. The expectation value of the squared deviations from the mean.

VCrossB.definition: The cross product of the charge velocity (V) and the magnetic field (B). It is the electric field exerted on a point charge by a magnetic field.

Vector.definition: A set of parameter values each along some independent variable (e.g., components of a field in three orthogonal spatial directions; atmospheric temperature values at several altitudes, or at a given latitude and longitude;).

Velocity.definition: Rate of change of position. Also used for the average velocity of a collection of particles, also referred to as "bulk velocity".

Venus.definition: The second planet from the sun in our solar system.

Version.definition: Indicates the release identifier. When used to indicate the release of the SPASE data model, it is a in the form Major.Minor.Fix where Major: A significant change in the architecture of the model or rewrite of the implementation. This includes major changes in design or implementation language. This number starts at 0 (zero). Minor: An addition of terms or features that require changes in documentation/external API. This number starts at 0 (zero). Fix: Any change that doesn't require documentation/external API changes. This number starts at 0 (zero).

Vertical.definition: Perpendicular to the plane of the horizon or a base line.

VolumeEmissionRate.definition: The volume emission rate, e(r, t, l), is the number of photons emitted per unit source volume per second, i.e. photons/(m3 s), as measured along the line of sight between the source point and the observer. The Volume Emission Rate is in general a function of the line-ofsight distance, r, time, t, and wavelength, l. The Volume Emission Rate is actually not a directly measurable quantity. However, the term has been commonly used in both data product descriptions and research publications.

VOTable.definition: A proposed IVOA standard designed as a flexible storage and exchange format for tabular data.

VSO.definition: Venus Solar Orbital - A coordinate system related to Venus where X is anti-sunward, Y along the orbital velocity direction.

Wave.definition: Periodic or quasi-periodic (AC) variations of physical quantities in time and space, capable of propagating or being trapped within particular regimes.

WaveForm.definition: Spatial or temporal variations of wave amplitude over wave-period timescales.

WaveformReceiver.definition: A radio receiver which outputs the value of one or more components of the electric and/or magnetic field as a function of time.

Wavelength.definition: The peak-to-peak distance over one wave period.

WavelengthRange.definition: The range of possible values for the observed wavelength.

WaveQuantity.definition: A characterization of the physical properties of a wave.

Waves.definition: Data resulting from observations of wave experiments and natural wave phenomena. Wave experiments are typically active and natural wave phenomena are passive. Examples of wave experiments include coherent/incoherent scatter radars, radio soundings, VLF propagation studies, ionospheric scintillation of beacon satellite signals, etc. Examples of natural wave phenomena include micropulsations, mesospheric gravity waves, auroral/plasmaspheric hiss, Langmuir waves, AKR, Jovian decametric radiation, solar radio bursts, etc.

WaveType.definition: A characterization of the carrier or phenomenon of wave information observed by the measurement.

Weak.definition: Slightly likely given the available evidence. Considered in the range of 1-4 on a scale of 0-10.

WebResource.definition: A Web page or file based resource accessible by a URL.

WebService.definition: A Web-based service that uses SOAP, WSDL or UDDI open standards.

WGS84.definition: The World Geodetic System (WGS) defines a reference frame for the earth, for use in geodesy and navigation. The WGS84 uses the zero meridian as defined by the Bureau International de l'Heure.

WhiteLight.definition: Photons with a wavelength in the visible range for humans.

WhitePaper.definition: An authoritative report giving information or proposals on an issue.

XML.definition: eXtensible Mark-up Language (XML). A structured format for representing information. See <http://www.w3.org/XML/>

XRays.definition: Photons with a wavelength range: 0.001 <= x < 10 nm.

ZIP.definition: An open standard for compression which is a variation of the LZW method and was originally used in the PKZIP utility.

AccessRights.name: AccessRights
AccessRights.definition: Identifiers for permissions granted or denied by the host of a product to allow other users to access and use the resource.

AdiabaticInvariant.name: AdiabaticInvariant
AdiabaticInvariant.definition: Identifiers for properties of a physical system related to periodic phenomena that remains constant under slowly varying conditions.

AnnotationType.name: AnnotationType
AnnotationType.definition: Identifiers for an classification of an annotation.

ApplicationInterface.name: ApplicationInterface
ApplicationInterface.definition: Identifiers for the type of interface for the application.

Availability.name: Availability
Availability.definition: Identifiers for indicating the method or service which may be used to access the resource.

ClassificationMethod.name: ClassificationMethod
ClassificationMethod.definition: Identifiers for the technique used to determine the characteristics of an object.

Component.name: Component
Component.definition: Identifiers for the axis of coordinate systems.

ConfidenceRating.name: ConfidenceRating
ConfidenceRating.definition: Identifiers for the classification of the certainty of an assertion.

CoordinateRepresentation.name: CoordinateRepresentation
CoordinateRepresentation.definition: Identifiers of the method or form for specifying a given point or vector in a given coordinate system.

CoordinateSystemName.name: CoordinateSystemName
CoordinateSystemName.definition: Identifiers of the origin and orientation of a set of typically orthogonal axes.

DirectionAngle.name: DirectionAngle
DirectionAngle.definition: Identifiers for the angle between a vector and a base axis.

DirectionCosine.name: DirectionCosine
DirectionCosine.definition: Identifiers for the cosine of the angle between two vectors in a three dimensional Euclidean space.

DisplayType.name: DisplayType
DisplayType.definition: Identifiers for types or classes of rendered data.

DocumentType.name: DocumentType
DocumentType.definition: Identifiers for the characterization of the content or purpose of a document.

Earth.name: Earth
Earth.definition: Identifiers for the regions surrounding the Earth.

Encoding.name: Encoding
Encoding.definition: Identifiers for unambiguous rules that establishes the representation of information within a file.

FieldQuantity.name: FieldQuantity
FieldQuantity.definition: Identifiers for the physical attribute of the field.

Format.name: Format
Format.definition: Identifiers for data organized according to preset specifications.

Hardcopy.name: Hardcopy
Hardcopy.definition: Identifiers for permanent reproductions, or copy in the form of a physical object, of any media suitable for direct use by a person.

HashFunction.name: HashFunction
HashFunction.definition: Identifiers for functions or algorithms that convert a digital data object into a hash value.

Heliosphere.name: Heliosphere
Heliosphere.definition: Identifiers for regions of the solar atmosphere which extends roughly from the inner corona to the edge of the solar plasma at the heliopause separating primarily solar plasma from interstellar plasma.

InstrumentType.name: InstrumentType
InstrumentType.definition: Identifiers for the type of experiment the instrument performs. This is the technique of observation.

Integral.name: Integral
Integral.definition: Identifiers for values above a given threshold and over area or solid-angle range.

Jupiter.name: Jupiter
Jupiter.definition: Identifiers for the regions surrounding the planet Jupiter.

Magnetosphere.name: Magnetosphere
Magnetosphere.definition: Identifiers for the region of space above the atmosphere or surface of the planet, and bounded by the magnetopause, that is under the direct influence of planet's magnetic field.

Mars.name: Mars
Mars.definition: Identifiers for the regions surrounding the planet Mars.

MeasurementType.name: MeasurementType
MeasurementType.definition: Identifiers for the method of making an estimated value of a quantity that forms the basis of an observation.

Mercury.name: Mercury
Mercury.definition: Identifiers for the regions surrounding the planet Mercury.

MixedQuantity.name: MixedQuantity
MixedQuantity.definition: Identifiers for the combined attributes of a mixed parameter quantity.

NearSurface.name: NearSurface
NearSurface.definition: Identifiers for regions of the gaseous and possibly ionized environment of a body extending from the surface to some specified altitude.

Neptune.name: Neptune
Neptune.definition: Identifiers for the regions surrounding the planet Neptune.

ParticleQuantity.name: ParticleQuantity
ParticleQuantity.definition: Identifiers for the characterization of the physical properties of the particle.

ParticleType.name: ParticleType
ParticleType.definition: Identifiers for the characterization of the kind of particle observed by the measurement.

PhenomenonType.name: PhenomenonType
PhenomenonType.definition: Identifiers for the characteristics or categorization of an observation. Note: Joe King to provide.

ProcessingLevel.name: ProcessingLevel
ProcessingLevel.definition: Identifiers to characterize the amount and type of manipulation which has been applied to the sampled data.

Projection.name: Projection
Projection.definition: Identifiers to projections into a coordinate system.

Uranus.name: Uranus
Uranus.definition: Identifiers for the regions surrounding the planet Uranus.

Venus.name: Venus
Venus.definition: Identifiers for the regions surrounding the planet Venus.

Qualifier.name: Qualifier
Qualifier.definition: Identifiers for terms which refine the type or attribute of a quantity.

Region.name: Region
Region.definition: Identifiers for areas of the physical world which may be occupied or observed.

RenderingAxis.name: RenderingAxis
RenderingAxis.definition: Identifiers for the reference component of a plot or rendering of data.

Role.name: Role
Role.definition: Identifiers for the assigned or assumed function or position of an individual.

Saturn.name: Saturn
Saturn.definition: Identifiers for the regions surrounding the planet Saturn.

ScaleType.name: ScaleType
ScaleType.definition: Identifiers for scaling applied to a set of numbers.

SourceType.name: SourceType
SourceType.definition: Identifiers for the characterization of the function or purpose of a source.

SpectralRange.name: SpectralRange
SpectralRange.definition: Identifiers for names associated with wavelengths. Based on the ISO 21348 Solar Irradiance Standard. Additions have been made to extend the frequency ranges to include those used in space physics. Those additions are indicated in blue text. The "Total Solar Irradiance" category has not been included since it is a type of measurement and not a specific spectral range. See Appendix A - Comparison of Spectrum Domains for a comparison of the spectral ranges with other systems.

Style.name: Style
Style.definition: Identifiers for the manner in which a response from a URL is presented.

Sun.name: Sun
Sun.definition: Identifiers for regions of the star upon which our solar system is centered.

SupportQuantity.name: SupportQuantity
SupportQuantity.definition: Identifiers for the information useful in understanding the context of an observation, typically observed or measured coincidentally with a physical observation.

Text.name: Text
Text.definition: Identifiers for the encoding of sequences of characters.

WaveQuantity.name: WaveQuantity
WaveQuantity.definition: Identifiers for the characterization of the physical properties of a wave.

WaveType.name: WaveType
WaveType.definition: Identifiers for the carrier or phenomenum of wave information observed by the measurement.

Waves.name: Waves
Waves.definition: Identifiers for experimental and natural wave phenomena.
